Description of Data

steak_survey_2 is a survey of 432 steak eaters in the US. It originally came from a surveymonkey audience poll, an online polling company.

steak chart!

Why this data?

In this data, we are going to be looking for influences that lead to type of steak consumed. * Relationship between demographics and food consumption? * Is the type of steak consumed associated with a higher status than others? * Mix of geography and sociology research

Research Question: what factor impacts the types of steaks people consume?

Response variable: steak_prep

Predictive variables: Region of US, Household Income, Age

Hypothesis

  • Region of US: Midwestern states more likely to consume rare steak due to high steak production and exposure to different cooking styles

  • Household Income: Wealthier people more likely to consume rare steak because it’s seen as a status symbol.

  • Age: Older People more likely to conume rare compared to younger people due to maturity.

Because all the variables we are looking at are categorical, we have decided to adjsut the data and divide them into two categories, as we intend to run logistic regressions later on. Rare and Medium rare are grouped together as “Relatively Rare”, and the rest is grouped together as “Not Rare”

This graph shows the types of steaks consumed by location. From these graphs, there are some notiable variations between regions. Some regions have more people consuming rare and medium rare steaks, including East Souch Central, New England, West North Central and West Souch Central.

Initial Modelling

We constructed one-variable logistic models with all three variables, and we mutated the data so we can see the odds with the variables. Here we set “not rare” as 0, and “relatively rare” as 1. In other words, in all these models, the odds are interpreted as the odds for liking relatively rare steaks.

We constructed one-variable logistic models with all three variables, and we mutated the data so we can see the odds with the variables. Here we set “not rare” as 0, and “relatively rare” as 1. In other words, in all these models, the odds are interpreted as the odds for liking relatively rare steaks.

Model based on age:

From this model, the predicted odds that a person below age 30 prefers rare steak is \(e^{-0.35020243}=0.7045\), or a probability of about 41.3%. These odds remain essentially the same for ages 30 - 60, but for people older than 60, they are multiplied by 1.32. Overall, this model shows little effect of age on steak preference, except that people older than 60 are slightly more likely to prefer rare steak.

Model based on income:

From this model, the predicted odds that a person with income below $25,000 prefers rare steak is \(e^{-0.5798185}=0.56\), or a probability of about 35.9%. These odds are multiplied by approximately 1.73 for both the $25,000-49,999 and 100,000-149,999 income brackets. However, for those with incomes over $150,000, the odds are decreased by a factor of 0.829. This indicates that the model predicts that the wealthiest people are actually less likely to prefer rare steak than the least wealthy.

Model based on region:

This model predicts that the odds that a person from the east north central region prefers rare steak is \(e^{-0.19671029}=0.8214286\), or a probability of 45%. There is significant variation between regions, with the odds for a person from the mountain region being the least, at \(0.8214286 * 0.3873518 = 0.3181818\), while the odds for the west north central region are highest at \(0.8214286 * 1.4983278 = 1.230769\).

We can conclude three different findings:
  1. The odds of people liking rare or medium rare steaks seem to go up with age groups, although the trend is not particularly strong;
  2. There does not seem to be a consistent relationship between income and how people like their steaks;
  3. And finally, East Souch Central, West North Central, New England, and West Souch Central seem to have higher odds of liking rare steaks. With the exception of New England, All these regions are in the middle of the country. Perhaps this means that middle America prefer rare steaks more than the rest of the country.

Modelling Test

In order to understand how strong these models are for further analysis, we will try to do hypothesis testing for all three of them. The null hypohthesis is that each of three predictive variables (age, income, region) does not have an impact on the responsive variable (steak preparation). The alternative hypothesis is that there are impacts. Since, all three models use only categorical variables, we will run AVOVA test for hypothesis testing.

To do so, we first constrcuted a null model with no predictive variable.

Then we use ANOVA to compare the null model to all three models

Unfortunately, all three models we have explored have overwhelmingly high p-values. Thus we can not reject any of the null hypothesis. Thus, even though some indicators (both region and age) the steak preferences of people, we can not affirm the relationship.
